<div id="review_904889211" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/904889211" />
    <a title="Angie Boyter" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3093693-angie-boyter"><img alt="Angie Boyter" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1318818152p2/3093693.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/904889211?book_show_action=true">Apr 08, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Angie Boyter" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Angie Boyter" href="/user/show/3093693-angie-boyter">Angie Boyter</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3093693-angie-boyter?shelf=didn-t-finish">didn-t-finish</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer904889211" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6615594948671217601">This is not a book that I think many general readers would enjoy. The first part is about the author&apos;s experiences building and running various tech companies and is fairly interesting. Most of it, though, is a huge compendium of short bits of management advice that gets very tedious. It might be of interest if I were looking for a how-to book, but, even so, it seems to be based pretty heavily on the author&apos;s own experience, i.e., &quot;I did this. I was successful. Ergo, this is the right thing to d</span>
  <span id="freeText6615594948671217601" style="display:none">This is not a book that I think many general readers would enjoy. The first part is about the author's experiences building and running various tech companies and is fairly interesting. Most of it, though, is a huge compendium of short bits of management advice that gets very tedious. It might be of interest if I were looking for a how-to book, but, even so, it seems to be based pretty heavily on the author's own experience, i.e., "I did this. I was successful. Ergo, this is the right thing to do." I suppose that is better than taking advice from a failure, but I would prefer more than one sample point.<br />I read it based on a positive mention in The Economist. I guess they are better at commentary than book recommendations.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6615594948671217601" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


