<div id="review_1842977719" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1842977719" />
    <a title="Sasha Malinovska" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/62662238-sasha-malinovska"><img alt="Sasha Malinovska" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1498684828p2/62662238.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1842977719?book_show_action=true">Dec 18, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sasha Malinovska" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sasha Malinovska" href="/user/show/62662238-sasha-malinovska">Sasha Malinovska</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1842977719" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16807961679596689959">Great book on how to be a successful CEO.<br/><br/>How to <br/>- fire people; <br/>- hire and integrate people (hiring right person for your company at this particular point of time; right kind of ambition);<br/>- train employees (productivity, performance management, product quality, employee retention),<br/>- make place a good to work in (where people can focus on their work and have confidence that if they get their work done, good things will happen for both them and the company = the work is efficient, effective, and ma</span>
  <span id="freeText16807961679596689959" style="display:none">Great book on how to be a successful CEO.<br /><br />How to <br />- fire people; <br />- hire and integrate people (hiring right person for your company at this particular point of time; right kind of ambition);<br />- train employees (productivity, performance management, product quality, employee retention),<br />- make place a good to work in (where people can focus on their work and have confidence that if they get their work done, good things will happen for both them and the company = the work is efficient, effective, and make a difference for the organization and themselves). <br />- avoid management debt and some other pitfalls; <br />- scale the company (communication, common knowledge, decision making); <br />- be a peacetime/wartime CEO (expnading the market/winning the market). <br />Being a CEO = making unnatural moves<br />-startegy+decision making = know what to do<br />-being a leader+having enough staff+having them deliver = being able to do what one needs<br />- delivering results.<br /><br />KEY TAKEAWAYS<br />Do not sell your company if<br />- the market is large and young,<br />- you have a good chance of being number one in that market. <br />a.k.a product-market fit in a bery large market with an excellent chance to be number one. <br /><br />Effectivness in company = intelligence+hard work+reliability+being a greatteam member. <br />brilliance+courage = enterpreneuership<br />ONE's (setting the direction)+TWO's(running everything smoothly) characteristics = successful CEO<br />Leadership <br />- ability to articulate the vision (story)<br />- having the right kind of ambition (take care of people)<br />- being able to achieve the vision (competence)<br /><br /><br />The primary thing that any technology startup must do is to build a product that's at least ten times better at doing something than the current prevailing way of doing that thing. The second thing is to take the market. Then you should think of your company's culture. <br /><br /><br />How to control one's nerves <br />-friends<br />-paper<br />-focus on the road<br />-do not quit<br /><br /><br />transparency rules<br />Good product manager vs bad product manager (take responsibility, know their stuff, decompose problems, assume others are smart, love clarity). <br />Decomposing problems. <br /><br />Nobody cares. Just run your company.<br />Use lead bullets = do not ignore issues and do not try to compensate it with silver bullets. <br /><br /><br />Being a great CEO = the ability to focus and make bset move when there is no good moves. Keep death in mind at all the times. <br />The Struggle is where greatness comes from.<br />Get maximum brains on the problem, don't take it personal, play long enough.<br /><br />Communication is the biggest problem in large organization. <br /><br /><br /><br />Following conventional wisdom and relaying on shortcuts can be worse than knowing nothing at all<br />What you defines you. Being scared while doing it - does not define you. <br />Balance between challenging each other and liking each other still. <br /><br /><br />Sometimes the things you're not doing are the things you should actually be focused on (ask it yourself, ask it other people on meetings). <br /><br /><br />When everything goes wrong ask yourself 2 questions<br />- What is the worst thing that can happen?<br />- What would I do if it happens? <br />When you don't know what to do at a regular basis: <br />- what does not seem as a waste of time? <br /><br />Calculations work in determinate world, probability and statistics work in indeterminate world. <br />Contingency plan can be handy, but you should not play odds. - up to person <br /><br />When you do not know all the pieces and is not asked for - provide info and data, not recommendations.<br />Efficient market hypothesis is deceptive. <br /><br />To build the right product: ship and try ti sell the wrong product. You would fall on your face, but you would learn fast and do what was needed to survive. <br />Figuring out the right product is the innovator's job, not the customer's job. <br /><br /><br />Know desicion-makers in every organization. <br />Whenever a large organization attempts to do anything, it always come down to a single person who can delay the entire project (less) </span>
  <a data-text-id="16807961679596689959" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


